<seg id=1> Zhejiang Province Students in Typhoon-stricken Areas Resume Classes </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> Xinhua News Agency, Hangzhou, September 2nd (reporter: Shen Haixiong and Shen Qixuan) The No.17 typhoon brought losses to educational systems in flood areas, with 1500 educational establishments ruined. </seg>
<seg id=3> Due to the active approach to dealing with the flood, the majority of middle and elementary schools had re-opened already. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> Education departments of Zhejiang Province had arranged for groups to go to Wenzhou and Taizhou to coordinate the resumption of education in flooded areas. </seg>
<seg id=5> The Education Committee of Wenzhou had organized over 20 teams to go to Leqing, Ouhai, Dongtou and Pingyang to help repair the school buildings and prepare for re-opening, and allotted RMB200 thousand of the education fund to deal expediently with the flood. </seg>
<seg id=6> The education and administrative departments of the flooded area had decided that reduce or waive tuition, or provide other aid. This allowed students with financial difficulties who could not pay the tuition because of the flood the opportunity to go to school on schedule. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> The leaders of the schools in flood-stricken area automatically went to work in advance, to clean up the school facilities carefully, sanitize, and repair the damaged or destroyed school buildings. </seg>
<seg id=8> The Education Committee of Wenzhou and Youth League Committee of Wenzhou united the teachers and students in the flooded area to launch the charity activity of "donation for the schools in flooded area", and had raised over RMB100 million from all circles. </seg>
</p>
